@using Fydar.Dev.WebApp.Components.Blocks.Phonetics
@using Microsoft.AspNetCore.OutputCaching;

@layout DefaultLayout
@page "/myname"

@attribute [OutputCache(Duration = 600)]

@inject NavigationManager NavigationManager
@inject Noncer noncer;

@{
    var openGraphModel = new OpenGraphModel()
    {
		Title = "Fydar - Name Pronunciation, Origin, and Meaning",
        Description = "My name is \"Fydar\". It's a unique name, so I decided to document it myself.",
        CanonicalUrl = "https://fydar.dev/myname",
        Properties = [
            new OpenGraphModelImage()
            {
                Url = "https://fydar.dev/media/header.webp",
                Alt = "A portrait of Fydar in an anime art style."
            }
        ]
    };
    var linkData = new LinkData()
    {
        new LinkDataBreadcrumbList()
        {
            new LinkDataBreadcrumbListItem()
            {
                Name = "My Name",
                Item = "https://fydar.dev/myname"
            }
        }
    };
}

<HeadContent>
    <OpenGraphComponent Model="@openGraphModel" />
    <LinkDataComponent Model="@linkData" />
</HeadContent>

<section class="container container-wide" data-nosnippet>
	<h1>My Name</h1>
</section>

<HeadingScope>
	<aside>
		<section style="position: sticky; top: 64px;">
			<div style="height: 5rem"></div>
			<TableOfContents />
		</section>

	</aside>

	<section class="container">

		<Heading Level="2" Identifier="history">
			<Text>History</Text>
			<Content>

				<p>In 2016, I began writing a novella featuring a character who embodied <b>humanity’s hope</b> for the future. Inspired by the name of King Minos’s daughter, <i>Phaedra</i>, I coined the name <b>Phaidara</b> (utilizing the Italian <i>-ara</i> suffix).</p>

				<p>As the character developed, the name evolved: first to <i>Fydara</i>, and finally to <i>Ismira, the Fydar</i> (where Fydar transitioned into a formal title). In 2019, Fydar became my primary username. By 2021, it had become the name I was most commonly known by, and I adopted it as my own.</p>

			</Content>
		</Heading>

		<Heading Level="2" Identifier="pronunciation">
			<Text>Pronunciation</Text>
			<Content>

				<audio id="pronunciation-fydar" preload="none">
					<source src="@Assets["media/pronunciation-fydar.mp3"]" type="audio/mpeg">
					<source src="@Assets["media/pronunciation-fydar.ogg"]" type="audio/ogg">
				</audio>

				<button class="phonetics" id="pronunciation-phonetics">/<span class="syllable1">&#x2C8;fa&#618;.</span><span class="syllable2">d&#x251;&#x2D0;</span>/</button>

				<script nonce="@noncer.Nonce">
					const audio = document.getElementById('pronunciation-fydar');
					const text = document.getElementById('pronunciation-phonetics');

					text.onclick = () => {
						audio.play();
					};
					audio.onplay = () => {
						text.classList.remove('readanimation');
						text.classList.add('readanimation');
					};
					audio.onended = function() {
						text.classList.remove('readanimation');
					};
				</script>

				<p><b><IPA String="new IPAString(IPACluster.PrimaryStress, IPACluster.F, IPACluster.Y, IPACluster.Syllabification, IPACluster.D, IPACluster.AR)" /></b> (Phonetic respelling: <b>FIGH-dah</b>)</p>

				<ul>
					<li><b>Fy:</b> Pronounced <IPA String="new IPAString(IPACluster.F, IPACluster.Y)" />, like the “fy” in <i>simplify</i> or “figh” in <i>fight</i>.</li>
					<li><b>dar:</b> Pronounced <IPA String="new IPAString(IPACluster.D, IPACluster.AR)" />, like “dar” in <i>dark</i> (British English) or “da” in <i>data</i> (DAH-tah, American English).</li>
				</ul>

				<p>I speak British English, which is a <b>non-rhotic</b> accent. Consequently, I do not pronounce a separate <IPA String="new IPAString(IPACluster.R)" /> sound (the "r" in "red") at the end of the name, unlike speakers with rhotic accents (such as most American English dialects).</p>

			</Content>
		</Heading>

		<Heading Level="2" Identifier="origin">
			<Text>Origin</Text>
			<Content>

				<img class="originchart" decoding="async" loading="lazy" src="@Assets["media/fydar-origin.svg"]" alt="The etymology of the name 'Fydar'." />

				<h3>The Stem: <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%CF%86%CE%B1%CE%B9%CE%B4%CF%81%CF%8C%CF%82"><i>phaid-</i><SvgSprite Link="/icons.svg?v=1#icon-external-link" class="external-link-icon" /></a></h3>

				<p>The prefix <b>Fy-</b> is a modernized phonetic evolution of the Ancient Greek stem <b>Phaid-</b> (φαιδ-), from the adjective <i>phaidros</i> (<a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%CF%86%CE%B1%CE%B9%CE%B4%CF%81%CF%8C%CF%82" target="_blank">φαιδρός<SvgSprite Link="/icons.svg?v=1#icon-external-link" class="external-link-icon" /></a>), meaning “bright,” “radiant,” or “joyful.”</p>

				<p>In the transition from <i>Phaid-</i> to <i>Fy-</i>, the “ph” undergoes a common historical shift from an aspirated stop <IPA String="new IPAString(IPACluster.AspiratedStop)" /> to the labiodental fricative <IPA String="new IPAString(IPACluster.F)" />, and the diphthong “ai” stabilizes into the long <IPA String="new IPAString(IPACluster.Y)" /> sound.</p>

				<h3>The Suffix: <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%D9%80%D8%AF%D8%A7%D8%B1#Persian" target="_blank"><i>-dâr</i><SvgSprite Link="/icons.svg?v=1#icon-external-link" class="external-link-icon" /></a></h3>

				<p>The suffix <b>-dar</b> is derived from the Classical Persian suffix <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%D9%80%D8%AF%D8%A7%D8%B1#Persian" target="_blank">ـدار<SvgSprite Link="/icons.svg?v=1#icon-external-link" class="external-link-icon" /></a> (<i>-dâr</i>). This comes from the present stem of <i>dâštan</i> (<a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%D8%AF%D8%A7%D8%B4%D8%AA%D9%86#Persian" target="_blank">داشتن<SvgSprite Link="/icons.svg?v=1#icon-external-link" class="external-link-icon" /></a>), meaning “to keep” or “to hold,” and is traditionally used to indicate ownership, agency, or one who possesses a specific quality.</p>

				<h3>Combined Meaning</h3>

				<p><i>Fydar</i> can be literally interpreted as “The Holder of Radiance,” or less literally interpreted as “The Keeper of the Light.”</p>

			</Content>
		</Heading>

	</section>
</HeadingScope>
